[3] Suspected, funding, research

3 Sep 2015 Gambia: Ebola is still in the sub-region
http://allafrica.com/stories/201509041209.html
[Sana Sambou, head of Disease Control and the National Incident Coordinator for Ebola, has cautioned the public that Ebola is still in the sub-region. According to Sambou, Gambia is termed as one of the most vulnerable countries because of its proximity to the epicenter. He said the country has a weak health system and, as such, they are taking advantage of the situation to see how best [the health system] can be strengthened not only for Ebola but any other current or emerging disease....more]

4 Sep 2015 Liberia: Gender documents 5716 Ebola orphans
http://allafrica.com/stories/201509041218.html
[The Ministry of Gender, Children and Social Protection said it has documented a total of 5716 Ebola orphans across the 15 subdivisions of the country. Of the 5716 orphans, 2996 were girls, and 2720 were boys. Madam Charlyn Worzie, who heads the Division of Children Protection at the ministry, told a child protection meeting on Tuesday [1 Sep 2015] the ministry through the Child Welfare Committee is providing assistance to the orphans through their guardians...more]

2 Sep 2015: Sierra Leone to vaccinate 200 people connected to Ebola victim
http://www.trust.org/item/20150902205652-2bw6i
[Following the death of a woman (a trader from the Kambia district near the border with Guinea], Sierra Leone is to vaccinate around 200 people who came into direct or indirect contact with the woman who died of Ebola on Saturday [29 Aug 2015], a spokeswoman for the U.N. World Health Organization said on Wednesday [2 Sep 2015]. ...more]

3 Sep 2015 Sierra Leone: Young nurse adopts newborn after mom dies of Ebola
http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/nationworld/ct-nurse-adopts-baby-ebola-20150903-story.html
[The 19-year-old mother clutched her newborn son as she arrived at the Ebola holding center. The baby's father was gone, and she had no family to help her. She knew she was dying. Nurse Donnell Tholley, 25, had seen hundreds like "F.T." in his work at Ebola clinics around the country. He knew to keep his distance, most patients would not make it, and any emotional connection would make the work even harder. ...more]

4 Sep 2015 Sierra Leone: Ebola doctor calls for fatal flaws in Sierra Leone health system to be addressed
http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2015/sep/04/ebola-sierra-leone-oliver-johnson-british-doctor-health-system

4 Sep 2015 Sierra Leone: More heartbreak for Ebola survivor after baby boy dies
http://news.yahoo.com/more-heartbreak-ebola-survivor-baby-boy-dies-121832077.html
[It was the new beginning that Sierra Leone's 1st Ebola survivor had yearned for after losing 21 of her relatives to the disease: a newborn who would allow her and her husband to start a new family.
But only weeks after the baby they named Barnabas was born, he died of an infection that overwhelmed his tiny body. In the Ebola-ravaged community of Kenema, the baby, who already had become a symbol of rebirth and renewal, was buried on Thu [3 Sep 2015], a day after he died. The cause of the baby's death was an infection and was not believed to be related to Ebola. ...more

Babies in Sierra Leone already faced some of the grimmest odds in the world even before the Ebola epidemic. Infant mortality is so high that tradition calls for children to be named only after they survive for a week. "A single case of Ebola catches the headlines, but nationwide, one in 11 children in Sierra Leone are dying before their 1st birthday, and that needs a stronger response," said Geoff Wiffin, head of UNICEF Sierra Leone.

This baby's death is particularly painful given the circumstances, but the rate of infant mortality, one in 11 children dying before their 1st birthday, cries out for attention. - Mod.LK]

5 Sep 2015 Sierra Leone: Village quarantined after Ebola death
http://allafrica.com/stories/201509050006.html
UPDATE:
1. Earlier this week, the [Sella Kafta village in the northern district of Kambia, Sierra Leone] was placed on high alert to ensure the virus wouldn't spread. A 3-week lockdown was announced on Fri [4 Sep 2015] for the village where the woman lived, affecting almost 1000 residents.
2. 48 of the villagers are considered high risk but have so far not shown any signs or symptoms of the virus.
3. Health workers were due to vaccinate around 200 people who had been in direct or indirect contact with the woman.
4. Officials said the woman had not traveled to Liberia or Guinea, which have also been affected by the worst-ever outbreak of the [Ebola virus disease, or EVD.]...more

3 Sep 2015 Sierra Leone/Cote d'Ivoire: Ebola--Federal Government screens Sierra Leone, Cote d'Ivoire footballers
http://www.punchng.com/news/ebola-fg-screens-sierra-leone-cote-divoire-footballers/
[The Federal Government [Nigeria] on Thursday [3 Sep 2015] in Abuja certified the visiting football players and officials from Sierra Leone and Cote d'Ivoire free of Ebola virus.]

3 Sep 2015 Sierra Leone and Guinea: Ebola Virus Disease -- Sierra Leone and Guinea, August 2015
S Hersey, LD Martel, A Jambai et al. MMWR early release
http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm64e0903a2.htm?s_cid=mm64e0903a2_e
[Abstract. The Ebola virus disease (Ebola) outbreak in West Africa began in late 2013 in Guinea (1) and spread unchecked during early 2014. By mid-2014, it had become the 1st Ebola epidemic ever documented. Transmission was occurring in multiple districts of Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone, and for the 1st time, in capital cities (2). On 8 Aug 2014, the World Health Organization (WHO) declared the outbreak to be a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (3). Ministries of Health, with assistance from multinational collaborators, have reduced Ebola transmission, and the number of cases is now declining. While Liberia has not reported a case since 12 Jul 2015, transmission has continued in Guinea and Sierra Leone, although the numbers of cases reported are at the lowest point in a year. In August 2015, Guinea and Sierra Leone reported 10 and four confirmed cases, respectively, compared with a peak of 526 (Guinea) and 1997 (Sierra Leone) in November 2014. This report details the current situation in Guinea and Sierra Leone, outlines strategies to interrupt transmission, and highlights the need to maintain public health response capacity and vigilance for new cases at this critical time to end the outbreak.]

3 Sep 2015 USA (Pennsylvania): Ebola scare shuts down Mercer County Correctional Facility
http://www.trentonian.com/general-news/20150903/ebola-scare-shuts-down-mercer-county-correctional-facility
[The Mercer County Correctional Facility is currently under lockdown due to an inmate who flew in from Liberia on 28 Aug 2015 and is experiencing a high fever, according to a report from WPVI.com. The inmate, whose name was not released, was brought in last night [3 Sep 2015] around 1800 hours and developed the fever around 200 hours. He was taken to an undisclosed hospital. WPVI reports the initial Ebola testing came back negative, but the facility will remain on lockdown until further testing occurs.]

4 Sep 2015 USA (Texas): Failures of Dallas hospital during Ebola crisis detailed in new report
http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2015/09/04/failures-of-dallas-hospital-during-ebola-crisis-detailed-in-new-report/
[Lack of communication among emergency room staff, poor configuration of information on the patient's electronic health records, and diminished focus on patient safety were 3 of the main deficiencies of Texas Health Presbyterian Hospital in Dallas during the 2014 Ebola crisis, according to an independent report released by the hospital Friday [4 Sep 2015].

According to the report, "The lack of complete history taking, particularly travel history assessment, documentation and sharing, the ineffective communications among the clinical team, and a seeming over-reliance on the EHR [electronic health record] rather than focusing on the complete care of the patient, leads the Expert Panel to recommend a broad review of the quality of care, IT [information technology], and the culture of the THD [Texas Health Presbyterian Dallas] Emergency Department"...more]
Texas Health Presbyterian Dallas: Ebola Event Report
https://www.texashealth.org/pages/about%20texas%20health%20resources/sharing-lessons-improving-performance.aspx

Funding
